{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/not-for-the-data-science-only-generate-matrices-together-with-numpy-d33f03d8875f", "time": 1683003802.917108, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/not-for-the-data-science-only-generate-matrices-together-with-numpy-d33f03d8875f/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Generate matrices together with NumPy | by Pavlo Horbonos | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Generate matrices together with NumPy", "description": "NumPy is on the Python libs which are initially associated with Data Science. Though, obviously, it is a universal instrument for processing arrays, matrices, and tables with a higher number of\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://docs.scipy.org/doc/numpy-1.15.0/reference/routines.random.html", "anchor_text": "provides a massive number", "paragraph_index": 3}, {"url": "https://twitter.com/MidvelCorp", "anchor_text": "https://twitter.com/MidvelCorp", "paragraph_index": 18}, {"url": "https://blaize.tech/", "anchor_text": "https://blaize.tech/", "paragraph_index": 18}], "all_paragraphs": ["NumPy is on the Python libs which are initially associated with Data Science. Though, obviously, it is a universal instrument for processing arrays, matrices, and tables with a higher number of dimensions. While the number of applications is too large to be described in a single article, I want to pay attention to a pretty useful feature: 2d-arrays generation. You may wonder, why should we even bother about it. So, I will remind about hundreds of a tiny operations we produce in every project and do not notice them: default variables\u2019 values generation, unit tests\u2019 data creation, preparing of the intermediate results, conversion matrices, \u201cdumb\u201d values, etc.. Preparation of such values takes some time and you will appreciate the necessity of them just before the finish of a project development.", "You may be surprised, as I have stated the 2d-arrays as the topic of the article. Though array to matrix conversion is very wide-spread, so this makes sense. Let\u2019s explore a pair of NumPy native tricks.", "Since we have the instrument to convert an array to a matrix, we can apply it to a traditional np.arange() sequence generator, for example:", "Of course, we cannot pass by the random sequences, since they are overused in testing purposes. Numpy provides a massive number of different random distributions based on different formulas. Though we will review the most common ways to create random matrices, all other methods may be used similarly:", "np.random.randn(3, 3) \u2014 3x3 matrix with the samples from a univariate \u201cnormal\u201d (Gaussian) distribution of mean 0 and variance 1", "Again we work with the arrays, but we cannot miss such important functions, which produce continuous distributions of the data in the stated interval.", "It is a good example of a filler function, which takes an array and replicates it several times to get a matrix. We have to set the number of row and the number of repetitions in a rows (in that order).", "For the intermediate operations with matrices, we may need the diagonal ones. Also, it is one of the basic elements in linear algebra. Not a surprise, that NumPy provides several functions for their creation.", "It creates a matrix completely filled with 0s. It is the perfect candidate for the default value of a variable or dumb return value.", "You can also use np.zeros_like() to create a 0s matrix with the size of a custom one.", "Another example of a default-valued matrix, filled with 1s for this time.", "Again, you can use another array as a template with np.ones_like().", "Previous functions create matrices with the defined filling values. But NumPy also provides a function for a custom filling.", "Another important element of the linear algebra operations: matrix a half filled with 0s. NumPy has three main functions for triangle matrices:", "The top of the NumPy functions mountain is np.fromfunction(). It creates a matrix of a custom size from the user-defined function. Function should take the number of arguments equal to the dimension of the matrix, and additional values, if need. Generation will start from the index (0,0) with the step 1 for each coordinate.", "You can find a complete notebook with examples on my GitHub:", "NumPy library is a perfect instrument for any linear algebra operations. It is full of interesting functions which can be used creatively. You are free to share your favorite NumPy tricks.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "Art & Code | https://twitter.com/MidvelCorp \ud83d\udcbb| Head of Blockchain Security in https://blaize.tech/ | web3 and blockchain enthusiast and researcher"], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2Fd33f03d8875f&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fnot-for-the-data-science-only-generate-matrices-together-with-numpy-d33f03d8875f&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fnot-for-the-data-science-only-generate-matrices-together-with-numpy-d33f03d8875f&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign In"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fnew-story&source=---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------new_post_sidenav-----------", "anchor_text": "Write"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/search?source=---two_column